<td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_05.gif" class="headerbg"><font class="h1font"><font color="#FFFFFF"><table cellspacing=0 cellpadding=0 border=0 width=100%><TR><td><font class="h1font">Articles</td><form method='post' action=''><input type="hidden" name="PHPSESSID" value="...328fedb22570524062aeb1303" /><td align='right' valign='bottom'><select name='select' onChange='go(this)'><option selected>More DeckTech Articles</option><option value='#'> </option><option value='/starwarsccg/articles/index.php3'>Star Wars: CCG</option><option value='/vs/articles/index.php3'>Marvel VS</option><option value='/heroclix/articles/articles.php'>HeroClix</option><option value='/lotr/articles/articles.php'>Lord of the Rings</option><option value='/magination/articles/articles.php'>Magi-Nation Duel</option><option value='/swtcg/articles/articles.php'>Ophidian 2350</option><option value='/magic/treports/treports.php'>The Wastelands</option></select></td></form></tr></table></font></B></td><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/red_06.gif"></td></tr>
	<tr><td background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_07.gif"></td>
		<td bgcolor="#FFFFFF" background="/lotr/gfx/mom/whi_08.gif"><font class="bfont"><font class="h1font"> Site One: Screwed Or Boost<br></font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Overall Rating:</b> </font><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><img src="/lotr/gfx/star2.gif" width="19" height="21" border="0" align="absmiddle"><font size='1'>(3.77)</font><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Author:</b> <A HREF='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=9724'>Benjamen "Lord_b3n" Lim</A></font><font class="afont"> <a href='http://www.decktech.net/lotr/main/mpage.php?member=9724&sub=1'> (Subscribe to this member)</a><br><font class="h2font"> <b>Date Submitted:</b> April 21, 2002</font><p align='justify'><font class="bfont"> Start: How much?<br />
<br />
Most LotR players are familiar with the start oeasterlingame of LotR. You have to place secret bids in your hand, and show simultaneously, then, the winning bidder gets to decide who goes first.<br />
<br />
There are basically five kinds of bids placed:<br />
<br />
0 tokens: these guys probably have no burden removal, and hence, they want to go little on burdens. Also, these guys might be nazgul players, and hoping to go second and get Weatherhills and ford in play, they would like to go second.<br />
<br />
1 token: these guys just cannot be bothered and feel like going first and not going first at the same time. These guys have no sense of direction and are normally free-frags.<br />
<br />
2 tokens: these guys are slightly better than one token bidders. They might want to go first and get their site one in play and hence, they bid two. These guys favour nazguls a lot, should they play The Prancing Pony, and add a burden for Aragorn, Dark Whispers and Damage+1 swords will come into effect.<br />
<br />
3 tokens: most of the time, these guys are Green Dragon Inn players. Either these guys play hobbit decks, or these guys just want to screw people who depend loads on The Pony. There are several assortment of these kind of guys, Shire lookout point, Fields (playing Pippin removes a burden) etc.<br />
<br />
4 and above tokens: these guys are suicidal, and should be looked upon as losers who want to go first at all costs.<br />
<br />
Bidding<br />
<br />
Bidding is a game of strategy in itself. Most players depend a lot on their site one. Aragorn players get choked up with Aragorn possessions if they go second and do not get Pony in play. Gandalf ‘s cart players get hands choked with possessions if they play many possessions. Basically, if you do not get your ideal site one, its more likely that you end up with a choked hand, and lose. <br />
<br />
Alternatively, if you depend a lot of your preceding sites, for example a nazgul player, you would be choked come your shadow phase, as you would not have enough twilight to play all your minions. This would also, in turn, let your opponent run to site 3, minion-less. <br />
<br />
Hence, it is important that you get your desired sites in play. Let’s address the Aragorn issue first. Should you want to go first, bid 0. then, you can count on your opponent’s decision to let you go first. These normally happens, in a scenario like this:<br />
<br />
Player: hmm….he bids zero, he surely does want to go second huh?<br />
Player 2: Grinnz<br />
Player: that’s it, he WANTS to go second. I’ll make him go first. HA, stupid nazgul player. <br />
<br />
As you can see, Player has been convinced into believing that Player 2 is a nazgul player. Therefore, to make sure he does not get his sites in play, Player makes Player 2 go first, enabling him to play The Pony.<br />
<br />
Alternatively, if you are chosen to go second, there are still ways of making you able to play Aragorn, or other crucial cards. The most obvious one would be to run multiple copies of the card you need. In this way, even if you cannot play them at site one, you can be sure you will get them soon. There is also through the help of  the shadow phase. Multiple copies of Ulaire Nelya can be played. Its useful test can changed site one into The Pony during your shadow phase, enabling you to play your Aragorn. Furthermore, there is also Paths seldom trodden, which also happens to be of nazgul culture. Hence, we can see that if you play nazgul, not only does it help if the opponent thinks you play nazguls by bidding zero, but it also helps when you want to change sites, to give you an edge of advantage.<br />
<br />
Site One: Foundation Comes From Here<br />
<br />
A good start in your game makes sure at least you can survive almost more than half of the nine sites. Thus, it’s practical to start flooding the twilight pool here. This is the onli time when you can be sure that you will not be screwed if you flood the twilight, as there are several sites that prevent shadow players to take advantage of the pool.<br />
<br />
Hobbiton Forest: Enables you to play your site 2.<br />
<br />
Should you want to flood your pool, you can be safe by playing a forest as your site two, and Ranger’s Verting all minions at site two that looks too powerful.<br />
<br />
Buckleberry Ferry: Skips skirmish if your whole fellowship only has hobbits.<br />
<br />
Viable to a hobbits deck, and all the allies needed can come out and flood the pool, and still, the hobbits need not face the minions that arise from the pool.<br />
<br />
And hence, site one is a good boost to a player, or a complete drag down to a player, and should always be considered with extreme consideration. Haha. Seeya.<br />
<br />
-ben<br />
